readability_reflection: I found string interpolation more readable overall. It reduces visual noise by embedding variables directly into the string, avoiding repetitive " + var + " patterns. For example, f"Hello {name}" is clearer and more concise than "Hello " + name. It makes it easier to understand the intended output at a glance, especially when multiple variables are involved.
comprehension_debugging: Yes — interpolation helped me understand the structure and meaning of the output faster. With concatenation, I had to mentally resolve the expression left to right, which can be error-prone if spacing or types aren't clear. Interpolation was more direct, and I didn’t have to worry about type conversion (e.g., numbers to strings) as much.
preference_rationale: I’d choose interpolation for most tasks because it improves readability, reduces syntactic overhead, and often prevents bugs related to spacing or type coercion. It's especially useful in logging, UI templates, and formatted output. Concatenation might still be useful in dynamic, loop-based constructions, but for clarity, interpolation wins.
learning_curve: My prior experience with both techniques helped me immediately recognize what the expressions were trying to do. I’m familiar with Python, JavaScript, and Java, so switching between + and {} representations was intuitive. That said, less experienced users might struggle with syntax-specific interpolation unless it closely resembles what they know.
suggestions_improvement: One improvement would be to enforce or recommend consistent spacing and formatting guidelines, especially in concatenation-heavy code. For interpolation, clearer delimiters (e.g., distinguishing between variables and functions) might help in complex cases. Also, IDE support and linting tools can help flag readability issues and auto-format expressions more cleanly.

readability_reflection: Based on my experience, I found string interpolation to be significantly more readable than concatenation. With interpolation, the variables are embedded directly within the string, which makes it easier to visualize the final output. For example, writing "Hello, {userName}!" feels more natural and clean than "Hello, " + userName + "!". Concatenation can quickly become cluttered, especially when dealing with multiple variables and longer strings, making it harder to follow the structure at a glance.
comprehension_debugging: String interpolation made it easier to understand and debug code snippets because the logic and output are more transparent. For instance, when I saw a line like "C://Users//{doc}//{userName}", I could immediately recognize the structure of the resulting path without mentally parsing multiple concatenation operations. In contrast, concatenation required more mental effort, especially when quotes and plus signs were nested or when multiple variables were joined. That added complexity can introduce bugs or make spotting errors more difficult.
preference_rationale: I would prefer string interpolation for future programming tasks. The main factors influencing my choice are readability, maintainability, and clarity. Interpolation scales better when strings get longer or when more variables are involved. It's also easier to modify and less error-prone, especially in dynamic environments where strings are built based on user input or configuration data.
learning_curve: My prior experience with both methods—primarily in Python, JavaScript, and C#—definitely made it easier to understand the examples. I’m more used to modern templating approaches like f-strings in Python (f"Hello, {name}") or template literals in JavaScript (`Hello, ${name}`). Because of this, interpolation felt familiar and intuitive. On the other hand, concatenation felt more reminiscent of older practices or languages with limited string handling capabilities.
suggestions_improvement: One improvement I’d suggest is ensuring consistency in syntax across different programming languages. For example, some use {} with $ or f, while others use %-style or function-based interpolation. A universal or more standardized approach could reduce confusion, especially for beginners. For concatenation, minimizing the visual clutter of repeated + operators (perhaps through a helper function or cleaner syntax) could enhance readability.

readability_reflection:

comprehension_debugging:
In string concatenation, it sometimes just takes you a second to gather your thoughts.

For example, when printing- 

"Water" + 4

I would need to run it and understand what will be printed, or if it will give me an error.

Whereas-

num = 4
"Water {num}"

This just feels right to the point. I have a variable that I want to plug after "Water"
preference_rationale: I would and have been using string interpolation for all my programming tasks, with a few minor exceptions here and there. As mentioned before, interpolation feels like a more solidified, grounded method.
learning_curve:
I have significant experience working in CS. I've worked on multiple projects, ranging from personal ones to production-ready ones for startups.

Recently, I've been working in inference engineering for Agentic LLMs, where I serve a system prompt with the tools embedded using string interpolation.
Example:

You are a helpful assistant. Please use the following tools to help the user.
Tools:
{tools}

Tools description:
{tools_description}
"""

readability_reflection: I prefer string interpolation rather than string concatenation. I found string interpolation more reasonable, as various languages handle string concatenation differently. For example, in JavaScript, it will type coerce numbers into strings and perform other abnormal operations. This prior experience hindered my understanding of reading string concatenation. However, string interpolation does not provide that ambiguity.
comprehension_debugging: String interpolation improved my ability to understand code snippets while concatenation hindered it quickly. String concatenation's use of the + operator can be interpreted differently depending on the language and can be ambiguous. String interpolation provides no ambiguity due to the + operator. However, string interpolation of constants was confusing. I had never used string interpolation to parse through integer literals (e.g. " {1} {2}") so it was confusing to grasp the new use case.
preference_rationale: I would choose string interpolation because of it is easier to refactor, less prone to error, and readability. It is easier to add a new variable into the string since there is no need to use the + operator and a new pair of quotation marks. It is less prone to error since it can be easy to miss a set of quotation marks in a large string. It is more readable as there is no extra symbols obfuscating the string.
learning_curve: My previous experience with string interpolation helped me understand the string interpolated strings better as it was my preferred way. My previous experience of concatenation hindered me as it was my unpreferred way and the + operator can be confusing.
suggestions_improvement: String concatenation should use a different operator than the + operator. The + operator should be reserved for arithmetic operations. Therefore, a different operator should be chosen. For example, in PHP, string concatenation is used with the . operator. (i.e. str = "My name is " . $name . "!"). This will clear up any ambiguity related to the + operator and type coercion.

readability_reflection:
In my personal opinion, I found string interpolation to be more readable. This is because the brackets {} bring more attention to the variable name, and the line of pseudocode is not covered by an abundance of plus symbols, which may make reading at a faster pace more difficult.

For example, here are some variables:
name = "Tom"
gpa = "4.0"

A sentence in interpolation: "Hello {name}, congratulations on passing with a {gpa} GPA!"
A sentence in concatenation: "Hello " + name + ", congratulations on passing with a " + gpa + " GPA!"

To me, the sentence in interpolation is easier to read.
comprehension_debugging: If the code is relatively simple, then both interpolation and concatenation is relatively easy to read. However, as it got more difficult, I found myself having an easier time with interpolation. But, if the provided code becomes incredibly hard to read, then it does not really matter how it was written.
preference_rationale: String interpolation is easier to read, but concatenation is easier to type. I think which one I would use depends on how I'm using the code. If I want to show my code to someone with no background knowledge on coding languages, I would use string interpolation, but if the code is mainly for my own personal use or I'm only showing the final output, I would just use concatenation.
learning_curve: I have never heard of string interpolation prior to this survey, so for the majority of the time, I had no idea if I was putting in the correct answers. However, once I understood how it works, determining the output became much easier. Concatenation was never much of a problem to begin with, provided that the provided pseudocode wasn't too complicated.
suggestions_improvement: I think both string interpolation and string concatenation are relatively easy to teach. It doesn't need any changing in terms of readability and comprehension, it really just comes down to preference. What really matters is how people would use it.

readability_reflection: String interpolation came across as more readable. It keeps the string structure intact and places the variables exactly where they belong, making the output easier to visualize just by looking at the line. For example, something like "Hello, {name}" reads naturally and mirrors the final output closely. Concatenation, on the other hand, breaks the string into several pieces and can get messy, especially when combining variables of different types, such as strings and integers. With concatenation, there's more room for mistakes like forgetting to convert an integer using std::to_string().
comprehension_debugging: Interpolation made it easier to understand the purpose of the code at a glance. When debugging, it was simpler to trace what the final string would look like without mentally stitching together multiple parts. Concatenation required more attention, especially when working with numbers, because forgetting a type conversion caused errors. In contrast, interpolation handled the formatting more smoothly and reduced the chance of those kinds of bugs. It also helped maintain clarity, especially in longer strings with several variables.
preference_rationale: String interpolation would be the preferred approach. It keeps code cleaner, reduces the need for manual conversions, and makes formatting more readable. In cases where multiple variables need to be displayed together, interpolation shortens the code and makes the intention clear. The main factors influencing this preference include readability, fewer chances for syntax errors, and easier debugging.
learning_curve: Prior experience with concatenation made those examples easier to understand initially, especially since they followed a familiar pattern using the + operator. However, after adjusting to the interpolation format, it quickly became clear how much simpler it was to read and write. Interpolation felt more intuitive once the syntax was understood, especially when working with multiple variables. Exposure to both helped reinforce the differences in clarity and complexity
suggestions_improvement: Allowing more natural mixing of types in concatenation would be a helpful improvement. Requiring manual conversions like std::to_string() can interrupt the flow of writing and make the code look more cluttered. As for interpolation, clearer support across environments or compilers would be beneficial. Having syntax highlighting or autocomplete features for variables inside interpolated strings could also make development smoother and help catch small errors early. Making interpolation a built-in and consistent feature would go a long way in improving string handling in general.

readability_reflection: For numbers, I especially found interpolation ("{}") more readable. When using the + symbol, I would often find myself confusing it with addition. For regular strings or when using variable names, I slightly leaned towards concatenation ("+") as being easier to read, partially due to my experience with using this symbol most often in my own code. That being said, the longer the sentence and the more often variable names are used, I leaned more and more towards finding interpolation more readable.
comprehension_debugging: Using concatenation did help me understand code snippets primarily in situations involving multiple variables or numbers, as there are no breaks in quotes when using concatenation. If there are many variables used during interpolation, it becomes more and more difficult to follow the quotes and determine where one part ends and a new part begins, as well as whether or not the code is written correctly or if, for example, the variable is accidentally written in quotes while the rest of the string is outside of it.
preference_rationale: I think I would prefer string concatenation for future programming tasks because, in my experience, I have experienced far less mistakes or errors on my end when using concatenation compared to the few times I have used interpolation.
learning_curve: Prior experience has absolutely impacted my ease of understanding the provided code examples, as I was fairly uncertain as to how concatenation worked, especially at the beginning of the study due to how little I have used it in the past or have seen it in my studies.
suggestions_improvement: I have no suggestions or recommendations on how either string interpolation or concatenation syntax could be improved to enhance readability and comprehension.

readability_reflection: I found string interpolation (e.g., using f-strings in Python) to be significantly more readable than string concatenation. With interpolation, variables are embedded directly into the string, making it much easier to see what the final output will look like.
comprehension_debugging:
Using interpolation made debugging faster because I could visualize the intended output without mentally parsing how each part connects. With concatenation, I occasionally had to trace back through each + operation, especially when combining strings with integers, which requires explicit type conversion in Python.

A challenge with concatenation is that forgetting to convert an integer to a string (e.g., + score +) raises an error, which can interrupt workflow and is less beginner-friendly. Interpolation avoids this issue because variables are automatically formatted within the string context.
preference_rationale: I would definitely prefer string interpolation for future tasks. It’s more concise, expressive, and avoids common errors like type mismatches. It also scales better for complex outputs such as logs, templates, or formatted messages. For instance, logging a file path or user action becomes clearer.
learning_curve:
Having prior experience with both methods helped me immediately recognize the strengths and weaknesses of each. I initially learned programming through concatenation, so I was comfortable with the syntax. However, once I started using Python’s f-strings and template formatting, I saw a significant improvement in clarity and productivity.

That prior knowledge helped me understand the examples quickly in the survey, but I can imagine someone new to programming might find concatenation more intuitive at first—until type issues or readability concerns arise.
suggestions_improvement:
For interpolation, Python’s f-string syntax is already quite elegant. One improvement could be built-in formatting rules inside the {} for better alignment or padding without needing external calls to .format(). Also, tools that highlight interpolated variables differently in code editors (similar to syntax highlighting) could help with comprehension.

For concatenation, perhaps simplifying how non-string types are automatically handled could reduce the need for str() calls, although that could impact type safety. Alternatively, providing warnings or hints when mixing types during concatenation could guide less experienced users.

readability_reflection: I found string interpolation more readable. Concatenation, with using +, was more confusing to read because I kept getting confused with arithmetic. Some of the examples in this survey included concatenations like (1+1+1+1) and it took me a few seconds to not read this as arithmetic but as string concatenation. With string interpolation, the strings themselves are defined as variables that are simply (visually simple to understand) inserted into strings like {string}, and it just makes it easier to read because the "{ }" can't be confused with other common symbols, like + for addition. Also, the "{ }" look like dividers which more clearly show where the string is being inserted. Concatenation doesn't have clearly visible barriers, unlike "{ }", so I also got confused with seeing where strings ended and started.
comprehension_debugging: Yes. Understanding the code with interpolation was much simpler than concatenation. With concatenation, it took time for me to see where strings ended, where strings began, where with interpolation I can more clearly see this division as well as visually understand how & where strings are being inserted.
preference_rationale:
I've had to do assignments and projects in the past where regular concatenation, with +, was simpler, but overall I tend to prefer interpolation. I have a lot of experience with using string interpolation in my projects that influenced my decision. To be specific, I do a lot of work with web development with Vue.js, and I use {{example}} a lot for string interpolation into my "html". An example is

Cost: {{cost}}

. Alongside these projects, and other projects, I've used a lot of TypeScript and JavaScript, and for printing statements (like cout and printf) with string interpolation, you would write console.log(`hello ${examplemsg}`);. I use string interpolation like this frequently for printing errors, like console.log(`Error: ${err}`);. So in Vue.js/TS/JS you can use {{ }} or ${ }. I don't really find myself using string concatenation as often as I do with string interpolation. The most useful example that I remember for needing string concatenation was for a recursive function of a tree, and basically the function needed to return a string, representing the path to a node (a leaf node), formed by concatenating "0"'s and "1"'s, depending on left/right path, as the function went up the tree from a leaf node and back to the main caller. Besides that though I would generally chose string interpolation.
learning_curve:
I use a lot of JavaScript (JS) and TypeScript (TS) with the Vue.js frontend framework for web development. To print statements in JS and TS with variables, you write console.log(`Hello ${name}`);. In Vue.js's "html", I use a lot of string interpolation for displaying dynamic data, like

Cost: {{cost}}

. "${ }" and "{{ }}" are the main ways that I regularly use string interpolation, and I use string interpolation much more regularly than string concatenation (although I remember having to use something like

{{firstName+ lastName}}

, and in this case concatenation is useful when I have user's names split between first and last name). Overall, my regular use of string interpolation made it much more easier for me to understand the examples. I regularly use string interpolation in similar ways that the examples provide.
suggestions_improvement: I think string concatenation is useful in some cases, with the two examples I provided being such cases. Overall though, unless the strings being concatenated aren't variables themselves, then in general it is easier to read code that uses string interpolation rather than string concatenation. Things like "1"+"1"+"1"+"1" can be confusing to read, but I feel like concatenation in examples like cout << firstName+ lastName << endl;, compared to string interpolation like cout << {firstName}{lastName } << endl;, are both fairly understandable to read (although I prefer the latter, and you could make it so adding a space w/ quotes like cout << "{myName} {lastName }" << endl; would generate a space in the console too). I'm not really sure of any other suggestions right now, but in general string interpolation makes code more easier to read than string concatenation in my opinion.

readability_reflection: String concatenation is more readable simply because it has less text to parse through. For example, if a = "(1" and b = "0)", then a + b is much easier to read than {a} {b}. However, it also depends on the context a bit. I like the interpolation of f strings in python, especially in an IDE that can color the interpolated section differently than the rest of the string. f"/Users/{user}/Downloads" is easier for me to read than "/Users/" + user + "/Downloads". So, I think if only variables are used, then concatenation is simpler. But if there is a mix of string with variables interspersed, interpolation is easier.
comprehension_debugging: Yes, interpolation vs concatenation affected my ability to quickly understand the code snippets. Just like the example I gave in 1, a + b is easier to read than {a} {b}, but f"/Users/{user}/Downloads"  is easier to read than  "/Users/" + user + "/Downloads".
preference_rationale:
If I had to pick, I would probably choose interpolation. In general, this type of thing comes up for me most when I am reading in files to pandas or numpy. In fact, I was recently working on a project where the original authors wrote out all of the file names as concatenated strings (in python). I will give a real example: 

genome_cov_file = data_path+'/data/'+cell_line+'/distal_reg_paper_bam/GM12878_DNase.bigWig'
seqs_bed_file = data_path+'/data/csv/seqs_bed/'+organism+'/'+genome+'/'+res+'/sequences_'+chr_temp+'.bed'
seqs_cov_file = data_path+'/data/'+cell_line+'/seqs_cov/distal_reg_paper/DNase_cov_RPGC_'+chr_temp+'.h5'

Seeing all of the quote characters can be a bit disorienting. This annoyed me enough that I rewrote them as f strings:

genome_cov_file = f'{data_path}/data/{cell_line}/K562_{epi_type}.bigWig'
seqs_bed_file = f'{data_path}/data/{cell_line}/seqs_cov/sequences_{chr_temp}.bed'
seqs_cov_file = f'{data_path}/data/{cell_line}/seqs_cov/signals/{epi_type}_cov_{chr_temp}.h5'

I much prefer the f strings.
learning_curve: I have good experience with both concatenation and interpolation. I would say that my knowledge or lack thereof did not affect my ease of understanding.
suggestions_improvement: I am not sure. An idea I have is to allow concatenation of strings only if there are no string literals being concatenated together, i.e. a + b + c. When you have a mix of string literals and variables, then interpolation should be enforced, i.e. "/Users/{user}/Downloads". Reducing the amount of characters to visually parse is the ultimate goal. Essentially, I am trying to eliminate unnecessary brackets {} for concatenation and unnecessary quotes "" for interpolation.

preference_rationale: Concatenation since I already use it in programming.
learning_curve: Already knowing concatenation was because that was what was taught to me in school.
